00:39:16.700 --> 00:39:20.500
in the world who has ever been
wronged by a man she loves,

00:39:20.500 --> 00:39:24.840
thank you for letting
Cash kick this guy's butt.

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:26.740
I mean thank you.

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:29.500
And we need that sequel.

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:31.700
&gt;&gt; Jesmyn Ward: Thank you.

00:39:31.700 --> 00:39:33.510
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Thank you ma'am.

00:39:33.510 --> 00:39:36.070
[ Applause ]

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:40.450
&gt;&gt; So my family too is from
Hancock County, though I am not.

00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:43.040
And while Katrina devastated
my family,

00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:48.000
I think in your novel it opened me
up to a perspective that I would,

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.770 position:56%
as a White woman, not naturally see.

00:39:50.770 --> 00:39:56.030
And I'm reminded of that as my
family is currently in Houston.

00:39:56.030 --> 00:40:01.790
And going through the destruction
in their lives and property there.

00:40:01.790 --> 00:40:06.160
But I think you've helped me
reflect on my battles are different

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:08.380
than other people's battles,
so I want to appreciate

00:40:08.380 --> 00:40:10.820
that in your fiction
and non-fiction.

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:14.540
But my question is do you feel

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:19.520 position:56%
like when you're reading fiction you
learn more about kind of humanity

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:22.270
and the past and things
like that, or do you feel

00:40:22.270 --> 00:40:28.080
like you do more so
through non-fiction?

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:32.410
&gt;&gt; Jesmyn Ward: That's
a good question.

00:40:32.410 --> 00:40:36.330
I don't know if I can quantify.

00:40:36.330 --> 00:40:39.340
I feel like - I really
think that everything

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:41.970
that I read teaches me
something, you know?

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:50.960
And that you know say when I need
to immerse myself in a story,

00:40:50.960 --> 00:40:56.650
you know in a fictional
story and you know go along

00:40:56.650 --> 00:41:01.820
with this experience that doesn't
mirror mine then I go to fiction.

00:41:01.820 --> 00:41:09.860
If I want more - and/or sometimes I
can do that in memoire too, right?

00:41:09.860 --> 00:41:17.500
Or if I want to learn more
than I know now then I'll go

00:41:17.500 --> 00:41:19.020
to creative non-fiction for that.

00:41:19.020 --> 00:41:22.830
I don't know, I feel
like I don't know -

00:41:22.830 --> 00:41:27.020
I feel like everything teaches me
something, every book gives me -

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:30.080
if I read it all the way
through it gives me -

00:41:30.080 --> 00:41:31.650
the reason that I'm reading it is

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:35.600
because it's giving me
something that I need.

00:41:35.600 --> 00:41:39.950
And so I don't - it's really hard
for me to compare the two genres

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:43.790
because they give me so much.

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:49.980
I don't know if I - I probably
didn't answer that so well.

00:41:49.980 --> 00:41:51.280
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I agree.

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:52.720
It's such a pleasure to have
you today, thank you so much.

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:54.520
